The following ode was written in honor of Augustus' return to Rome in the spring of 24 B.C. after an absence in the West of nearly three years. ’

‘Our Caesar, a second Hercules, comes home victorious from the Spanish shore. His faithful consort, his sister, all ye matrons with your children, should give thanks to the gods. For me this day puts all care to flight: so long as Caesar rules Ι have no fear of civil strife and violence. So. boy, bring unguent, flowers, and good old wine, that Ι may celebrate this festival.
